<activity xml:id="act-uSubPicking">
    <title>Picking the Pieces of a Substitution</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            We're going to look at three integrals. Instead of working through them one-at-a-time, we'll look at all three simultaneously, where we can practice identifying, substituting, and antidifferentiating all at the same time.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let's consider these three integrals:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{3x^2+1}{(x^3+x-2)^2}\;dx</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int \cos(x)\sqrt{\sin(x)}\;dx</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{(\ln(x))^3}{x}\;dx</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                For each of these integrals, identify the substitution: define <m>u</m> as some function of <m>x</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
            <p>
                Can you find the composition in each one? If you notice the function-derivative pairing instead, then you can think about making <m>u</m> the "function" portion!
            </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{3x^2+1}{(x^3+x-2)^2}\;dx</m>, let <m>u=x^3+x-2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>\displaystyle \int \cos(x)\sqrt{\sin(x)}\;dx</m>, let <m>u=\sin(x)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{(\ln(x))^3}{x}\;dx</m>, let <m>u=\ln(x)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </answer>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For each substitution, define <m>du=u'\;dx</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>u=x^3+x-1</m>, <m>du=(3x^2+1)\;dx</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>u=\sin(x)</m>, <m>du=\cos(x)\;dx</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>u=\ln(x)</m>, <m>du=\frac{1}{x}\;dx</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </answer>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For each integral, use your substitution (for both <m>u</m> and the differential <m>du</m>) to re-write the integral.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle\int \frac{3x^2+1}{(x^3+x-2)^2}\;dx =\int \frac{1}{u^2}\;du</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int \cos(x)\sqrt{\sin(x)}\;dx = \int \sqrt{u}\;du</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{(\ln(x))^3}{x}\;dx = \int u^3\;du</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </answer>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Antidifferentiate each integral, and then use your substitution to write each integral back in terms of <m>x</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\int \frac{1}{u^2}\;du \amp = -\frac{1}{u}+C</mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{x^3+x-2}+C</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\int \sqrt{u}\;du \amp = \frac{2 u^{3/2}}{3}+C</mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{2(\sin(x))^{3/2}}{3}+C</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\int u^3\;du \amp = \frac{u^4}{4}+C</mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{(\ln(x))^4}{4}+C</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
            </p>
        </answer>
    </task>    
</activity>